    "summary": "The Battle of Blenheim (August 13, 1704 AD) was the greatest Allied victory of the [[event:2347|War of the Spanish Succession]], at which the Duke of Marlborough (John Churchill) and Prince Eugene of Savoy decisively defeated the combined Franco-Bavarian army at the village of Blindheim (Blenheim) on the Danube, saving Vienna from capture and marking the first major defeat of Louis XIV's forces in decades. The battle was the culmination of Marlborough's brilliant strategic maneuver: secretly marching his Anglo-Dutch army from the Netherlands to Bavaria (a 250-mile, five-week march) to link up with Eugene's Austrian forces and prevent France and Bavaria from knocking Austria out of the war.\n\nThe battle itself was a masterpiece of deception: Marlborough pinned large French forces on both flanks (drawing them into the fortified village of Blenheim and the Lutzingen woods) with feints, while concentrating overwhelming force in the weakened center. The Allied cavalry broke through the French center, then turned to roll up both flanks; the French forces in Blenheim — an estimated 27 battalions — were surrounded and forced to surrender. French casualties were approximately 30,000 killed, wounded, or captured (out of 56,000); the Allied victory was complete. The battle shattered French strategic ambitions in central Europe and demonstrated that Louis XIV's armies could be defeated in the field. In recognition of the victory, Queen Anne gave Marlborough a royal estate at Woodstock, where Blenheim Palace was constructed — birthplace of Winston Churchill two centuries later.",
